[SLE virus is found very sporadically in Texas. The last ProMED-mail posting of human cases was in 2010 (see St. Louis encephalitis - USA (03): (TX) conf. 20101103.3975), and those occurred in Nueces County also. From 1990 to 2010, 74 people in Texas tested positive for St. Louis encephalitis virus infection, according to the Texas Department of State Health Services. Unlike West Nile virus, St. Louis encephalitis comes in spurts, and most years, there are no cases of the mosquito-borne disease found in humans, according to state records. The last Texas death from the virus was in 1995.

The virus also is found in the southeastern USA with occasional incursions into the midwestern states and in the western states of California and Arizona. The USA Centers for Disease Control and Prevention indicates that less than 1% of St Louis encephalitis virus (SLEV) infections are clinically apparent, and the vast majority of infections remain undiagnosed (https://www.cdc.gov/sle/technical/symptoms.html).

Wild birds are the SLE virus reservoir hosts, and mosquitoes in the genus _Culex_ are the vectors that transmit SLE virus. The mosquito species in which SLEV was detected are not mentioned in the above report. - Mod.TY

